One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Contrary to what happens in Canada, American states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And along the same lines, a majority of American governments enacted new laws since 2009 that made it difficult to register or vote.
This phenomenon has spread following the November 2010 elections, which saw an increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 restricting the exercise of voting rights in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present an identity card with a photograph, as well as proof of American citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on polling day, and withdraw the right to vote from citizens with a criminal record.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no American state required voters to present an identity card with a photograph.
The State of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The United States Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana law in 2008.
Therefore, the Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present an identity card with photography.
It is important to bear in mind that, contrary to what happens in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as the Social Security Card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack such an identity card.
But, often, obtaining the required identity card costs more than $100.
Thus, the new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25 per cent of African-Americans, 15 per cent of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18 per cent of citizens over 65 years of age and 20 per cent of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have a photo identity card.
And there's more.
In many states students, voters who vote most for Democratic candidates, cannot use the photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote for Republican parties to use documents issued by such clubs.
Prior to 2004 no state required the citizenship test to vote.
Arizona was the first state to file such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to demonstrate that they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit the Hispanic vote.
It appears that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic party.
On the other hand, Republican legislators supported in 2011 certain laws that abolished voter registration on the same day of the election in eight states.
They also limited the right of individuals and groups to set up a help desk for voters wishing to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
Measures taken since 2009 brought the registration rate of new voters down in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators adopted laws in five other states that favoured reducing the period of advance voting.
For example, in the 2008 Florida elections, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while the latter accounted for only 13% of the state's voters.
In the case of Hispanics, the exact same thing happened.
They represent only 11 per cent of voters, or 24 per cent of citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who represent 76 per cent of the electorate, represent only 46 per cent of citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have fervently opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
In this regard, Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The United States Attorney General's Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
In part, damage could be limited.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states adopted the law requiring the presentation of a photo identity card.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, as it is clear that they are intended to influence the 2012 results in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that have adopted such laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to achieve the presidency.
It is too early to state with certainty whether these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
