The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson generated a great shock last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, in fact, that this boson is a participant in the mechanism responsible for the mass of all that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what is more, it is the particle whose existence predicted the standard model: our best or "less bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists it's not entirely clear that it's about Higgs.
We know without a doubt that there is a new particle and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, new data revealed this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data is still missing to be completely safe.
Anyway, we assume it's about Higgs, because the chances of being wrong seem slim. We'll see what it's about.
There is, in this great world, a generalized and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There's no way to break that rule and don't try too hard, because it'll end up hurting you.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also in it a law of these characteristics: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantity state"; a "state" consisting, grossly, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we find the good citizens called fermions, who obey wisely at the beginning of Pauli.
And on the other hand there are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of Berkeley Laboratories which, by the way, is extraordinary, bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, of which we will not speak here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, one might stress here, are not the exotic bugs we could believe.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the "light particle" that acts as a "message" of electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disorders" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a little like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave is born (from light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the bosons "force carriers".
More stable field
The same is true of the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "unordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it it requires reaching extremely high energies, a little as if it were an iced pond in which only a thick rock could slide down the surface.
That is why it takes a huge particle accelerator such as CERN (the great hadron collider is a ring of 27 km of circumference!) to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do it, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never stand by itself attached to the door of a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), do not have it.
Now, what "can all these investigations contribute?" asks Mrs Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between MS observations and predictions.
For their part, many fervently want them to meet, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that plugs certain holes in the model.
This, it has to be said, still has enormous shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation regarding gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the Universe (another ups!).
But we have not found such differences in CERN so far.
Impact
The impact of such research on our day-to-day lives is difficult to predict, but we do not believe that we are wrong to say that it will have none.
For you to see: in the early 1960s, laser pioneers in laboratories did not suspect at all the revolution that their work would provoke.
They entertained scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who produced the first continuous laser (the first being pulsed) in 1962, at first the laser was rather considered a "laboratory aparate".
Imagine...
Moreover, applications can also come from all the instrumentation surrounding research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself produced a light catcher in 1969 in the course of his optical research.
Although it was not at all his original intention, this catcher now serves as an "eye" for all digital devices in the world, which earned him the Nobel Physics Prize in 2009.
