Bitcoin differs from other systems with virtual coin types such as "credits", used to advance in a video game and which can be won by playing or can be purchased (and sometimes even redeemed).
The social network Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange a central authority controls and treats changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are both depositaries of accounting books, verifiers, currency issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is electronically signed through a dual-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the bitcoins changes are contained in the public account book, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge to computers and the winner, a kind of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
It is a phase of file cutting, that is, of transforming a large file into a shorter and more unique numerical footprint.
Computers "cook" the new transaction and add a number before "trace" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more zeros at first).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the set chain of other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, in order to commit a fraud, one user wanted to pay twice with the same money very fast (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would remain orphan, since both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is divided into two regularly, likely before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to one hundred millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in the calculus power.
The life of the network already has its ups and downs.
Websites offering services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen in storage.
"The failure used does not affect the same protocol," says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-currency payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But cash has the same defect.
Major actors such as Wikipedia reject payments of this kind.
Others, such as the Wordpress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, from Insitito Weizmann in Israel, analyzed the ledger and showed that about 80% of bitcoins are not circulating.
In November the "giant sales" were launched.
"They changed $30,000," rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who turns bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogic book on that currency, believes quite well in the potential of this technology in addition to the network of transactions.
Your system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a non-contact mobile payment, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus come out cheaper.
The bearer also manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to put into operation in shops, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
They simply provide an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of revision of hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
"It will take a while for Bitcoin to prevail, but in 2013 there could be a change," he predicts.
Moreover, in its report the ECB intends to reassess the various risks, which are now considered high, if this currency succeeds.
