A forceps constitution in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, he decided to play everything for the whole.
He caught everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of State had given the Assembly two more months to complete its work.
And for almost two years Egypt has been using a provisional text, several times modified, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial embroilment.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his "autocratic delirium" and continues "treasoning his word" and "pissing the right".
On the part of its supporters, it ensures that this is a step towards ending the institutional and political crisis more quickly and accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be organised within the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that obliges the Brothers to renounce their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy wreaks havoc throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in his favor, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this remedy has been voted on very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "either they vote my text or maintain full powers", powers that are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment that 85 members of this Islamist Constituent Assembly, the vast majority of them, voted on the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not attend the call.
By mid-November, a little before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be achieved, 11 people, substitute members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brothers.
As expected, the articles voted unanimously.
Commentators are also pleased that one of the few discrepancies of the day has been expressed practically at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the Constituent's clock was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2 of the Constitution of 1971, which stipulated that “the principles of Sharia constitute the principal source of law”, remains the same as article 2 of the Constitution.
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that “principles” could be replaced by “rules”, which would have allowed for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
Liberals call it hypocrisy and consider it nothing more than an advertising ruse.
According to them, Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer in particular to article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular for anyone who is to confirm its conformity with the laws of the Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to pronounce themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we see the premises of a theocracy."
Liberal fears are further heightened by the fact that the next rector of that university would be much less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution we are in the framework of civil status.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not ulemas but university students, some of them trained in the French system," explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, as the terms used imitate religious vocabulary.
"We refer specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that might be asked in the future would be to what extent are the civil judges competent to pronounce themselves above all this."
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms that refer to the extended powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brothers will claim that there are few compared to those who were during the previous regime.
Another conflicting point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the revision of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Nor will prosecutions of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as called for by associations for the defence of human rights.
They also showed their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticide.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and insults are now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially in the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, stresses Heba Morayef, of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing had been the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was supposed to be on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this noon.
Supporters of the head of state demonstrated on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for the holy land, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the majesty of Bible truths with modern comfort and pristine nature.
"AIF" identified the five most important reasons why Israel should be visited.
Reverence in the Holy Land
It is worth visiting the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that anyone entering this "baptismal pile" will receive divine grace.
And Galilee, the place of Jesus' miracles: the conversion of water into wine at the wedding, walking on the waters, the calming of the storm and the crowded nets.
In this same place, Jesus appeared before his disciples after the resurrection.
But the largest number of holy places is in Jerusalem.
The believers travel here the Viacrucis or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin "Via Dolorosa").
It begins in the Fortress of Antonio, the Praetorium, where the trial took place, and continues through the streets of the Old City, goes to the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, the place of the crucifixion, the Stone of the Anointing and the burial place of Jesus.
In this same place is also the symbolic Christian navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem, built in the place where, according to a Christian legend, there was a tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place for Jews, the Wall of Lamentations; the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
As is tradition, people of different religions leave notes here with their desires, which will then come true.
Take a vertical journey
It was the ruins of the Masada Fortress that remained of a secret refuge against enemies, which Herod the Great had built in 25 B.C. for his family.
They are located on the mountain cliffs at a height of 450 m above sea level.
And to get there by their own means, can only those who engage in climbing.
The others can reach this historic summit on the funicular.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m you will find the famous Hermon ski resort, where in the winter months there is a large influx of tourists.
Bus services are available from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods supposedly lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
In this country there are about 300 museums.
On a single trip you won't be able to visit them all.
But it is worth visiting at least five of them, the most interesting.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, located near the Knesset (Israeli Parliament).
It preserves the ancient Manuscripts of the Dead Sea or Qumran Rolls, discovered in the caves of the Judean desert, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological pieces.
It is worth visiting the Museum of Art in Tel Aviv.
In his exhibition of paintings he features canvases by impressionists and expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall or Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the Al Basha bath museum, which are some rooms of ancient Turkish baths with model figures of visitors and bathers of that time.
In Cesarea it is worth going through the exclusive private museum Ralli, where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin and Dalí.
There are no tourist guides or souvenir shops there.
Admission is free, and donations are categorically not accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, shows one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic section is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars are shining.
And the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they lost their lives ring.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health
The three main tourist areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of them there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanographic museums.
It is curious that in the Red Sea they bathe even in the winter months, since the temperature of the water does not fall from 21 degrees and the air heats up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and there they bathe all year round.
By the way, this sea, the most extraordinary in the world, is at the lowest point on the planet: 417 m below sea level.
The blue waters there are brine that easily sustain even those who can't swim.
The surrounding landscapes are truly beautiful.
People come here to pass treatment courses with salt water, brine and healing muds and to fortify their health in cases of dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to put their broken nerves in order.
Touching the Mysteries of Antiquity
They are preserved by the ancient part of Tel Aviv, the citadel of Jaffa, on the Mediterranean coast.
Through it passed the famous maritime route that linked Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda with whom, in this very place, he led a long and happy life.
Tourists love to stroll through the narrow streets that bear the names of the signs of the Zodiac.
They say that if you touch the walls in the street of your "self" symbol, fortune will be favorable to you.
In Jaffa you can find couples of newlyweds who come from all over Israel, and even from other countries to be photographed.
And in Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theatre, "take" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The theatre, carefully restored, is now used for night concerts and opera shows.
Tourists remember
If you travel to Israel, do not worry if your English leaves much to be desired: in this country about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
The money for this trip is not recommended to carry it in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily changed to shekels (currently 1-3$,8 shekels).
Urban transport is mainly made up of buses, but in Jerusalem there is a fast tram and in Haifa is the only metro line in the country, which consists of six stations and connects the Lower City with the Upper City.
Actually, it's from an underground funicular.
Traveling on any type of public transport costs 6 shekels and for this price you can travel by transhipment for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, Sabbaths are celebrated.
From Friday night until the sunset on Saturday, markets and shops close and public transport interrupts their work.
But Sunday morning starts a new work week.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels only kosher food is served, excluding pork, seafood, flakeless fish and dishes that combine milk and meat.
There is a wide selection of dishes based on beef and lamb, soups and desserts prepared with coconut milk, the traditional Hebrew cream called hummus, a variety of sauces, the falafel, which are ground chickpea balls, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
Instead, there are many well-fed cats who "walk to their liking" in an imposing way.
At night you can see them sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
Roarers love crowded places and don't reject treats.
Renting a car, depending on the brand, will cost $37 (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) a day.
Besides insurance, it comes out for $15 a day.
And the rent of a bike will come out for 15 shekels a day.
Entrances to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
Israel in figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of those who came to tour the country and rest were citizens of the US, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, United Kingdom and Ukraine.
The Promised Land, from January to October 2012, was visited by 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists, an amount that is 51% higher than the same rate in 2010, before the cancellation of the visa regime on February 9, 2011.
"The great and powerful" will take you to Moscow: immigrants save for the language
While deputies and human rights defenders discuss the consequences of the law on compulsory examination, scammers who trade in "false" certificates have already appeared in the country.
Every year, 13 million immigrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families who have stayed home.
Since 1 December, a law has entered into force, according to which each migrant worker must take an examination to check his or her knowledge of the Russian language.
For the time being, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service delivery sector, community service institutions, domestic services and retail trade.
However, over time, as promised by the Federal Immigration Service, examinations will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will not be enough to take the language test, but also that of Russian history and the fundamentals of legislation.
Knowledge of the language must be confirmed even in order to receive and renew the work permit.
Exceptions are made for citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Persons who obtained their education and diploma certificates prior to the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991 shall not be subject to this law.
Utility, fatality and defence of rights
The network of examination centres will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, the People's Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take tests in all cities, right now in Russia more than 160 such centers are open.
The initiative on the introduction of the review was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Immigration Service.
But the defenders of rights, long before the law came into force, were many times able to ask this question to the press: And what will this actually bring?
What changes will the compulsory knowledge of the language bring, both for Russians and for immigrants themselves?
First, the representatives of the Immigration Service respond, this will reduce the number of people suffering from "labour slavery".
Many people are talking today about defending the rights of labor immigrants, explains Victor Sebelev, head of the representation of the Russian Federal Immigration Service in Tajikistan.
The defence of his rights must begin before his departure.
Only an organized selection system will solve the problem of migrant workers in 90 per cent of cases.
The problems are faced by immigrants without a profession, education, those who do not know the language or pass medical control.
Without the understanding of the language, Sebelev says, the future immigrant will be condemned to find unscrupulous people who, under the pretext of helping, put a "paid little trip" into a creepy, narrow covacha, where he and dozens of others like him consume themselves for months without food or documents, working 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive countless complaints from our immigrants.
"In their homeland they are promised one thing, but when they arrive they are deceived, they are deprived of their passports, they are not paid the wages promised," confirms the head of the Labour Immigration Directorate of the Tajik Immigration Service, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't be angry, Chief!
Meanwhile, however, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who wish to work in Russia recognize that they not only do not know the language of the country they intend to go to, but also write with difficulty in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much his fault but his own misfortune: few Turkmenos, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to receive normal primary education.
This is because their families even have nothing to feed the children, let alone dress them up, fit them and buy them what they need for school.
Upon reaching adolescence, these boys venture to work at the first chance.
It's hard, if you don't know the tongue, they recognize it.
"One feels humiliated and inferior."
However, as far as the language law was concerned, defenders of rights pointed out an important point.
The examinations will be conducted only for those immigrants whose status is legal.
If they do not have that status, there will be no examination and, consequently, no official work.
Meanwhile, most immigrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or forbidden passage to strangers"
Many visitors claim that receiving official status in our country is not that easy.
The cause lies in bureaucratic obstacles and in the difficulties of the language itself.
In addition, legalization costs money: from twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a false inscription can be made quickly and for only 1,500 rubles.
Russian police employees know that we usually carry false documents, we are not registered and extortion cases appear.
"They ask us for a hundred or two hundred rubles for cigarettes or tea," Tajik citizen Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
"Come on, don't be cheap, buy a painting."
On the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it became clear that not only immigration registration documents can be false.
Several "false" certificates of language proficiency have already been seized by Federal Immigration Service officials.
The forged documents had been printed on standard color printers.
Of course, they came into the hands of the new owners not as a gift: each immigrant, wanting to facilitate the task of passing the tests, paid for the document 7,000 rubles.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official examination procedure, which will cost the immigrant worker 3,000 rubles.
The main task for the near future is to protect the system from corruption so that "diplomas" cannot be bought, government officials and rights defenders converge.
So far, the authorities can promise immigrant workers that they would not have been able to successfully pass the test the first time more time to study the basic language course.
In addition, non-Russian-speaking immigrants will be offered jobs that do not require active communication with people.
