Employees of fast food restaurants and supermarkets in the U.S. are on strike.
Up to a quarter of American teenagers find their first jobs as cashiers at "McDonald's"
In the past few days, a wave of protests against the low wages paid in Walmart corporation supermarkets and in restaurants of popular fast food chains, such as "McDonald's", "Burger King", "Taco Bell", "Wendy's" and "Kentucky Fried Chicken", have begun in the United States.
For now no one dares to assert whether or not this wave will reach the nine points, or whether it is destined to lose strength and become tame in its early stages.
Protest actions are supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing NGOs.
In addition to the increase in the modest wages received by Walmart workers and those of the fast food system, the aim of the organizers of the protests is the creation of workers' unions in these companies.
For now, this sector of the economy has hardly been occupied by the trade union movement.
Forty-six cents a year?
The actions began last week, after Thanksgiving, the so-called "Black Friday." That day, in the United States, the orgy of rebates that captured millions of inhabitants, and that was sometimes accompanied by confrontations, began.
On that day, some workers of the Walmart corporation, which employs 2.2 million people around the world, left their jobs and formed protest pickets alongside trade unions and left-wing activists in the corporation's stores, whose products are aimed at modest and moderate-income people.
Walmart sells everything from diapers, hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The products in their stores are on average between 8% and 27% cheaper than those in the larger supermarkets.
That's why many low-paid Walmart workers buy only at work.
The availability and assortment of products have made Walmart one of America's largest corporations.
According to two critics, Walmart can afford to sell products at very low prices, partly because it pays little to its workers.
The latter also complain about poor working conditions, such as the lack of forklifts or hand scanners.
That "Black Friday" protest participants demanded the increase in wages and complained that the cost of health insurance provided by the corporation went from $30 to $100 a month.
For a typical Walmart worker, who receives $9.5 an hour, this spending is excessive, they said.
Scientists at the University of California at Berkeley argue that if Walmart raises the average wage to $12 an hour, this will cost the corporation $3.2 billion.
This is about 1.1% more than it spends on wages now.
If Walmart places the wage increase on the shoulders of consumers, each visit to the store will be only 46 cents more expensive.
In a year they will spend the ridiculous amount of $12.39 more than they now spend.
Walmart supporters are pleased to note that the protest took place in only nine states and that it caused no loss to the corporation.
The "Black Friday" lasted in its stores from 8 p.m. on Thursday until midnight the following day and, during that time, Walmart sold around 5000 items per second.
In total, their cash registers carried out the "Black Friday" almost 100 million transactions.
The company's representative, Dan Fogelman, stated in an interview to the left-wing website Huffington Post, that they left their job "less than five" Walmart employees and that the protest had been just "another public relations trick", organized by the workers' union.
"Free box!"
Protests continued this week in New York, where the targets were not precisely the Walmart department stores (which in this progressive city have no appreciation for them, and so for now there are none), but the McDonald's and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald's says he sells billions of portions, and then they don't even grant you sick leave and don't pay you for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, New York City Council Member
Currently, according to federal and New York law, the minimum wage is $7.25 per hour.
Fast food restaurants are increasing it over time, but only slightly, and on average, regular workers receive $8.90 per hour in New York City.
No one wins less than them in this city.
How it's possible to survive in New York with that money, to me it's incomprehensible.
There was a time when nearly a quarter of American teenagers went through the McDonald's and worked there, behind the counters, part-time after school, although they still lived with their parents.
Few saw this as the main source of income or planned to stay there for a long time.
Now, I constantly stumble into some interviews with McDonald's workers who complain that they have to live off this salary, and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, on a Wall Street Journal magazine forum there is a comment whose author points out that it is irresponsible to have children if he does not know what to feed them with.
Participants in the protests, which began at 6:30 a.m. on Thursday at McDonald's on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashiers and fast food cooks start paying at least $15 an hour, that is, double their current minimum wage.
They also demanded that workers' unions be established in the fast food sector.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from denying them this right and punishing union activists with trickery and layoffs.
On the other hand, administration rarely makes life easier for them.
But for objective reasons, it is easy for trade unions to cover the fast food sector.
One of the main ones is the excessive turnover of staff.
Discordants
Noisy protests took place that same day in other cheap restaurants in Manhattan.
The culmination of the action took place midway through the McDonald's rally near Times Square, in which several local Democratic politicians participated, in particular City Council member Jumaane Williams, who said, "McDonald's says he's selling billions of portions, and then doesn't even give you a hospital or pay you for your honest work."
Protesters were supported by other prominent New York Democrats, for example City Mayor Bill de Blasio, who said that "we must support fast food workers to get fair wages and the economic prosperity every New Yorker deserves."
As described in the New York Times, this has been the largest manifestation of this kind in American fast food history.
But only a few hundred people participated in it, not all of them were employees of the fast food service, in which tens of thousands of people from New York work.
It is not yet clear whether this will spark a massive movement.
"For now, fooling the brain isn't that easy."
The topic of augmented reality, so popular among modern technology enthusiasts, is lately perceived normally mainly through the prism of special glasses.
At the beginning of the summer, at its annual conference Google demonstrated a model in motion and later, in November, it was learned that Microsoft had also filed an application to claim the corresponding patent.
However, from a conversation with the head of the interactive 3D technology group at the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge, Izadi Sharamom, it was diluted that for the scientists of that company, the glasses already belonged to a past stage.
They are attracted to the perspective of the manipulation of virtual objects in the air with bare hands and the creation of open virtual spaces.
- Please, in general terms, what is the subject of your research group's study?
- We are dedicated to person-computer interaction, but we also try to broaden the limits of this interaction.
For now humanity in its great mass has been trapped in the working stage with the pixels of the flat screen, sometimes touching it with the finger.
But we want to look 5-10 years ahead and guess the cardinal changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors represent a step forward and today no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What else does the future hold for us?
- Although Kinect has taken interaction to the physical level, much of it still occurs on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The introduction of information has improved (the system receives more data), and the output is still not very good.
We're trying to change this, we're working on truly three-dimensional visualization systems, based on different technologies, including design.
The world of computing must be freed to ours, to the physicist, to make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user, but also the space around him.
Then we can complete the real world with virtual objects in a more comfortable way.
First of all, screw those dumb virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
A very popular detail, but don't you think they overestimate it?
- Of course you can't consider it a panacea, you still have to solve the question of privacy, because you don't always want others to find out about our actions and intentions.
In fact, all types of interaction with computers are good, but each in its own field.
For example, for the control of devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought of gestures, but not of loose movements, but shorter ones.
In addition, the gestures were captured not by the device's camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movement of bones and muscles.
For now it is very large, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But, in general, the future is for a combined type of control, for example gesture + voice.
- How's that?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass you this soda can?
You will speak and show it at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, that's going to be very hard to recognize.
- I mean, you want to force users to adapt to what they can or can't do right now the machine?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual approach.
I think in the near future we're going to have to work mainly on designing new types of sensors that can accurately determine the person's reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, as they provide good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- If we talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what complaints do you have about modern cameras?
Are they missing resolution, depth or something else?
- In principle, the current generation is what can be the beginning of our work with three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be good to get 8 megapixels at the speed of 1000 fps.
But the question is not in the megapixels, but in the quality of the matrix and in the depth.
From this last point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us; this gives more work to algorithm designers.
So we have to remember not only the resolution on the X and Y axes, but also on Z.
Speed is also important, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic and current movements of 30 fps are truly scarce, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, from our Redmond laboratory, made a contact sensor with adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 ms and it is worth mentioning that the modern serially produced sensors are closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands to what extent this affects man-machine interaction.
It would be very useful to me for my work an equivalent of such a device, but that does not require contact to make the frames per second more.
- And there's no need to increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three cameras, one of which is in fact the infrared emitter and the second the receiver of the reflected signal.
But the third camera is actually a simple sensor of the visible fingerboard.
This is not used to determine the depth of the object.
Potentially, more cameras could solve the problem...
Or on the contrary, increase it and increase the required amount of calculations.
It would be good to create a flexible Kinect analog, play with the location curvature of the cameras and see how this would help determine the three-dimensional position.
- As far as I remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, hasn't presented its glasses to the public.
Don't you think that, from the point of view of the daily use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most visible platforms?
- Of course, spending all the time holding a smartphone up in your hands, it's not very comfortable, but I think: the best option would be a "transmutable" augmented reality when, based on a cloud platform, you could move from glasses to smartphone,
The glasses are very personal devices, in that is your strength (private things only you can see them), but also your weakness: an augmented reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects together with other people.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark of the film "Iron Man", but also to any simple mortal.
There is a problem with this idea that critics often point out: there is no tactile answer!
Hands don't feel anything!
What answers does your group prepare for this challenge?
- In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh irruption in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth might well be the addition of tactile sensations.
Meanwhile, one of the most interesting tricks is the use of the second hand as an image support.
Keep track of the touch perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are truly aimed at bringing tangibility to these "images in the air." For example, the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed to a specific point where the finger is located gives a feeling similar to what one feels if someone was blowing it into the fingertips, but that feeling is still very weak.
There are also wrist bracelets that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, this also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to fool the brain?
Make him think he feels what it looks like he should feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried yet.
Here is another challenge with which we will have to fight for a long time, how to make a person physically located in a very small space believe that he goes to an open space, almost endless. We are also working on the idea of treadmills (not like gymnasiums), mobile platforms, as well as giant balloons.
For now, deceiving the brain is not so easy, we still have to work for many years.
That's what makes working with virtual reality attractive to researchers, which many things are in a state of total conception.
