Earth is in danger.
Global warming or collision with a killer asteroid.
Spaceship caravans with humans on board leave in search of a spare planet.
To preserve humanity, the main question is: How to continue the species in conditions of weightlessness or on the same spare planet?
I think there's little to choose from.
In fact, only two are true planets that can be colonized, at least hypothetically.
"These are Venus and Mars," says the head researcher of the State Astronomical Institute, Sternberg P.K. (IAES), Vladimir Surdin.
But if conditions on Mars are better for life, on the surface of Venus the temperature is 500 degrees.
You can only live at high altitudes or in the orbit of Venus... in space.
The problems of reproduction in space with flora began to be addressed.
Experiments with plants have been carried out for half a century now.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit did not differ in any way from terrestrial varieties.
Then came the breeding of insects in the orbit, small fruit flies, the drosophiles.
In 1979 quail eggs were sent into space to check how the embryo develops under weightless conditions.
We get a normal chick as a result.
But then the trouble starts.
"The problem is that this chick has to find support, it must stay on its own feet and start moving," explains Vladimir Sychev, the director of the laboratory of the Institute of Biomedical Problems (IPBM) of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
Not finding support, the chicks gave random flips.
And after 10 hours in newborns there was a total atrophy of instincts.
The chicks did not react to light or sound.
And the misfortune was that after four days they would just die.
"And twice we got the chicks born, but then we left it because it was impossible to work there with them," comments Vladimir Sychev on the failure of the experiment with the chicks in space.
The last time a biological miniarch flew into orbit was 16 years ago.
Experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, in the biosatellite "Bion" only species of the same sex will travel.
There was an experiment with rats, which were sent into space already with fetuses.
In principle, nothing supernatural was found.
"This was precisely in biosatellites, but this was a unique experiment, and studies like this must be carried out," says Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, space rats had offspring.
However, the problem of reproduction directly in space has not yet been addressed.
