At the meeting of the supervisory committee in the Congress of Deputies, you spoke of the common project between the Czech and German teams, in the framework of which the legislation concerning public awards in both countries was compared.
What exactly is it?
This is a parallel control that we began to carry out about two years ago.
Simply put, European legislation regularizes how public awards should be organised, followed by legislation in force in each country and then praxis itself.
We have brought everything together and, although the control has not yet been completed, we have obtained very interesting differences. Generally, our country's legislation is "stricter and more complete", but concrete praxis in some parameters is better in Germany.
It is therefore confirmed that it is not enough to incorporate ever stricter rules, but that it is necessary to concentrate on the implementation of the law itself.
What can this project actually contribute? What do you think the conclusions are?
It is precisely such a common control that could help us to stop investing in the enforcement of laws, the reduction and improvement of limits, even if this does not have such a positive impact.
The economy of savings means getting a right thing at a reasonable price (which does not always mean that the price is the lowest) in order to avoid enrichment and, in the long run, criminal actions.
But not by reducing the award limit means that we are going to achieve it.
Perhaps because the system is saturated with so much "papering", that those who want to look for system failures can do so more easily than if the limits were kept as high as now.
