Public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to make a comparison without specific data. However, Germany remains a model in some respects, but it cannot be precisely specified where it is best.
Could it be better, for example, as regards the quality of inspectors?
That's for sure not, but, I repeat, I don't like to make these kinds of comparisons.
It must be said that even those countries that we take as models must face a large number of problems.
If you didn't, you wouldn't have any benefit in collaborating with our office, would you?
With regard to the legislation of our country, what did the amendment of the law on public awards mean for your Office? Is it in any way manifesting its impact?
Given that the validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been expressed in the supervisory proceedings.
Since we carry out ex post checks, we need to have a certain delay.
For the time being, it is evident in the process of preparing future controls: we have started a new tool of "detection of non-economic risks", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process are rectified and similar.
Do you consider that the adoption of this law is beneficial or rather a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope so.
The problem that may arise is that the regulation is "hardened" and that it is impossible to comply with it.
Already under the previous regulations, controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes of the regional council), and each law not respected in the matter of public awards meant a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it then make sense to harden the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal decision, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We will see where this initiated path leads us.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the SDG would not disturb entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called švarc system, with reference to being autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the švarc system forbidden or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits anything, then not even the prime minister of the government can prevent the Office from acting which has an obligation to carry out such controls and to demand obligations.
You can say, "We change the law and allow it," but you can't say we're gonna act like nothing.
In the law on public awards, the law is quite strict as to how formal action should be taken, and this is how it should be in order to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate is excluded with the best offer for not meeting the formal demands.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
