Movie Argo: If it gets raw, call Hollywood
In November 1979 a group from the Islamist student demonstration occupied the American embassy in Tehran and took 52 graduates as hostages.
His release was to be in exchange for the dethroned Shah Mohamed Réza Páhlevi, who after the revolution fled to the US, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration the situation did not offer any positive prospect: throwing the Shah overboard could not allow it, since, if it did, it jeopardized the confidence of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not within their reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which subsequently intensified further with the failed attempt to release the hostages by force.
Imprisoned diplomats were released 444 days after the Algerian government's negotiating intervention.
In the US, his fate caused a wave of solidarity and animosity against Iran.
The failure in Iran contributed decisively to Jimmy Carter's defeat to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck tracks an episode of this story, which garnered a small success for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated journey, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian embassy.
CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helping a covert story an extravagant point: they went out with Canadian passports, as members of the film team that examined the location in the country for the filming of a science fiction superproduction.
Combination of genders
The plan drawn up by "exfiltration" expert Toni Mendez required Hollywood collaboration.
To make the lie seem truthful, it was written about the film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictional production society had even a real office.
Details about the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is a singular combination of various genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that went well, a deception (an example may be the Ocean's Eleven series).
The film combines moods. On the one hand we find well-documented sequences from Tehran. The sequence of credits shows emblematic photographs of the time of events, which were similarly reflected in the film; there are not many differences in this respect.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes somewhat lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And also, scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions: men in suits who analyze the situation at the negotiating table, in the corridors of the office, by phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been mocked, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Goodbye Little, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film in which the action takes no place in the city of Boston, where he grew up.
Likewise, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed the directors of old films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck shows it in Argo, where Tehran runs in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place on the streets, in the reconstruction of the true events. The introductory sequence of the embassy takeover is impressive for its synoptic ability which, at the same time, conveys the emotion of bewilderment and lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, history takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect on fictional scenes (the impostor team in the Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story does not offer much in the cinematographic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
And he manages quite well. Sometimes he adds something to reality: here everything doesn't come out so elegantly (the scene in which the crisis is lurking at Tehran airport, the diversion of a call to America and the rampant search behind his trail turn into madness).
Argo's weakness is the uncontrollability that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are by no means the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck's film loses some dramatic stroke, but it is a film that can be followed with moderate interest, value its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 70s.
But if it collapses, that will be difficult.
As an evocation of a real history and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of secret services may be, it is sufficient.
