The MVRDV architecture studio shows that the real adventures are not only in the head - in the example of Spijkenisse's library and the recently completed "book mountain" - 2 photos
"I think the building is fun, it looks futuristic, and at last there's something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby passing through the street.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician at a large company located near the library, says, "In addition, the building is beautiful."
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have the Internet, tablets and e-books.
No one enters those old-fashioned libraries for pleasure, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town located at the gates of Rotterdam that hardly deserves a fleeting visit, has the dubious honor of having risen with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this shameful situation, some years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture and copy the seven fictitious bridges that appear on euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that's how policymakers decided that there was only one way to improve statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture firm MVRDV, a master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun and cynical buildings, took the subject with his usual serenity and appeared at the presentation of the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked perplexed around and shrugged, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size into a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here it is, my proposal for the book mountain of Spijkenisse, the so-called `Boekenberg'."
Nine years later, the EUR 30 million mountain rises at its intended location.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of housing and townhouse buildings.
In early November the book mountain was awarded the second "Best Library of NL 2012" award.
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the small city without history, which to date had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white facade one would rather intuit a dairy plant, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long way to the book
The first impression is that this is a book paradise under a cheesebox.
Well it is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountain massif, but the true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to merge with its topography at every step of its climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to cover with the view, the annealed brick floor and the elegant lanterns unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
When you look up you can see the park benches, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"Normally bookshelves are arranged along the façade and in the center there is a huge dark room that usually is uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
What we have done is turn the classical spatial configuration upside down and take the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well used: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention should be made of the black shelves that assume the functions of wall covering, parapet and railing at the same time.
Eyesight, touch, and smell are strange.
Even architects and civil engineers more frequently shake their heads when they hear of this unknown material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, head of the project in the city of Spijkenisse.
And that's how one day, on a Frisian farm, we come across the right byproduct from agriculture.
For many years now, in the greenhouses and fields of the Netherlands, a plastic fabric of only a few millimetres thick has been used as a basis for holding the roots of crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine fabric lasts two seasons and is then discarded.
For the library this fabric was primed, for the first time in such quantities, to obtain plates four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a new car mix and sport shoe.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain the reward awaits us: from the cafeteria not only has a fantastic view of the city, but in it you can also enjoy tasty Dutch croquettes and its ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere while maintaining the right atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
"Even if it's hard to believe given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling is obtained from geothermal energy.
Even though the book mountain is situated under a huge crystal pyramid, even on the sunny days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden fences across the glass façade serve to shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is about automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the sceptical IT worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has also been there.
Similarly, traditional Chinese medicine teacher Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library. She describes the "Boekenberg" as Spijkenisse's "late soul".
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way it is intended to fill, for the moment, the optical holes of a library that does not yet have its complete archive; at present it has 70,000 copies.
The concept has gone deep.
The shelves are packed.
"There is nothing worse than an empty half-library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain link with this building.
Everyone knows his book is part of the library.
Even if I'm just there to decorate.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved a great success in that discipline reigns that in the specialized slang is known as "creation of an identity".
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of the history of literature.
No matter how young and uneducated he may be.
Finally a starting point to shape their identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a more leading role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert in US-Europe relations, this puts Berlin in a rather harsh diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany suggested that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories observer status to the United Nations.
However, Berlin finally abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, because of the special relationship that unites the country with Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time I do not think he supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it was about establishing a no-fly zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stance when important international issues are at stake?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is currently re-orienting its foreign policy, moving away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and focusing on a German foreign policy.
What makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
The Germans are therefore at a crossroads.
From them they are expected to play a more independent role, but are not accustomed to doing so.
I think they're still testing their role, but they've already started the road to a "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to countries like France or Britain.
What does a German 'normal' foreign policy mean in particular?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy finds strong motivation in economic policy, i.e. in exports and in its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other major powers and for that reason Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position taken with regard to the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
That is why he must be careful and not alienate himself from Arab public opinion or the Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I would not attach such importance to it because it is not a totally one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a fundamental role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the United States by abstaining from voting on important decisions such as the Palestinian vote?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position enjoys an enormous degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not believe that there has been such a drastic break-up as in the case of Libya.
Perhaps Germany has managed to gain some respect from this.
After all, all this has shown that it is a country that they take seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
There are different views in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
On the other hand, the US has clearly been in favour of a veto.
Is there a disparity of views between the US and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of U.S. domestic policy.
I believe that the Obama administration secretly shows a great understanding of the European position.
But, because of the political situation here, it is clear that the government cannot defend this position in public.
I believe that the true disparity of views does not really have the magnitude that is attributed to it.
If we look at the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about the policy he is developing.
