"Mark Protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese brands
Armani is a world-famous brand and Polo Ralph Lauren as well.
But what is Armani Polo?
Behind this name is a name officially registered in China but which has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it enjoys protection as long as the real ones do not file a claim.
And even then it's not clear that they're going to be right.
"Foreigners find it increasingly difficult to protect their brands in China," says Thomas Pattloch, attorney for the Taylor Wessing law firm specializing in protection rights violations in the Far East.
A new case comes to my table every week.
Impersonators simply add a couple of letters to register their marks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada is registered Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied in the same way, as has happened to the Puma sports goods manufacturer.
Pattloch opens a filing cabinet where he keeps seats from the Beijing brand office.
On 14 September 2010, a Chinese company applied to register the brand Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name also used by the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In the big cities there are department stores of several plants dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, Pattloch's cases are of a different nature. On behalf of his clients, he fights against the fact that the trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to take advantage of a denomination that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or accompanying brand.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
which refers to women who have "fished" a rich man.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty
"It's harmful to the business, we have to fight it," demands Pattloch.
"The brand makes water, the monopolistic position disappears and the damage to the image is enormous."
The financial losses and procedural costs of the sectors concerned are millionaires, especially in the case of emblematic luxury products.
According to data from the market analysis company CLSA, with a volume of 15 billion euros per year China is, in size, the third largest and fastest growing market for luxury goods.
However, it is complicated to have the registrations of dubious legality annulled and it also means a lot of money.
Processes can be extended to nine years and the result is uncertain.
Pattloch talks about cases in which the court dismissed a claim because so long had passed that the name the claim had already become a “market reality”.
"If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay money to the plagiarist because the process has damaged China's brand," Pattloch says.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the best known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that has recently been absorbed by German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That is why today the Chinese can continue to use an emblem very similar to the star of Mercedes.
Volvo's buyer Geely initially used a white and blue logo that largely reminded BMW; the matter was settled in court and Geely had to modify it.
The clothing manufacturer Lacoste lost in China to copycats from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo represented a crocodile looking in the opposite direction to the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO brand office in Beijing acknowledges that in 2010 they had difficulties due to the shortage of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, "the labor emergency situation returned to normal."
Thus, the amount of unprocessed claims processes has been reduced by 22 per cent.
Almost 57,000 of these cases were resolved, 75 per cent more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 claims remain outstanding.
Fighting this costs a lot of money.
As is usually the case in China, the figures are surprising.
Last year CTMO registered more than 1.4 million applications for trademark protection, almost a third more than in 2010.
It would be a new record and means that China leads the list of new entries around the world for the tenth consecutive year, according to the brand office.
This also seems to be the case with the number of valid logos, a figure of 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan would have been bagged for rights.
In other words, this means that on average each registration costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting against this costs a lot of money, as shown by the case of the German family business Freudenberg.
For more than seven years the group has been fighting in court against a Chinese copycat.
While the Germans have managed to stop the illegal manufacture of imitation car parts,
the impersonator has managed to secure Chinese rights over the Freudenberg brand.
"We ourselves have caused this situation because in Germany surnames are not protected," says Hanno Wentzler, President and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The CTMO Trademark Office also rejected the appeal of the Muniques.
In the following two instances Freudenberg has been found right, but the opposing party continues to fight today.
You have to be very careful.
The case has now reached the gates of the High Court of Justice, where it is still pending resolution.
Wentzler hoped to be able to resolve the matter favourably and commended the professionalism of the courts.
However, he also states that "the procedure is extremely costly, both in terms of money and time."
It is difficult to estimate internal costs; the business archive has had to review files up to a hundred years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the opposing party a "sum of six figures in euros" with the aim of reaching a friendly agreement, but it was not successful.
"This shows how much we care," Wentzler says.
The dangers lurking in the Far East threaten even to affect Europe,
in particular, whether copycats secure the rights to unprotected trademarks there.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register in Germany the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather products.
The group had long since left this commercial area, but had been able to prevent registration.
"We have to be very careful," Wentzler says.
Both he and attorney Pattloch recommend that German companies be extremely prudent in doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international trademark law, but what needs to be done is to "register also in China everything that can be protected", as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the topic can be much more expensive than a simple record.
In fact, in case Freudenberg lost the last assault of his particular battle, he would then have to pay the opposing party license fees by his own name, as Wentzler explains.
That or the segment in question would drive us out of the market.
World AIDS Day: dancing, singing, helping
In Heidelberg, the Imbongi choir rehearses, and in Swaziland, AIDS orphans rejoice.
The story of a bond capable of overcoming much more than 8,733 kilometers away.
First you start with the dance: cowboy boots, basketball shoes, heel shoes and moccasins look for the compass on the parquet floor, and find it quickly.
One, two, three, four.
Only then do the vocals of the singers (contralto, bajo, tenor and soprano) slowly begin to rise, swirling, hindering and following each other.
And Fiete Hopf, the 29-year-old director, threatens to get almost out of his way by trying to put order with his energetic and soft gestures.
It is Monday afternoon and in the music room of the Heidelberg Institute of Medical Psychology the Imbongi choir rehearses a new song.
The fifty singers, between the ages of 23 and 69, have also arrived from the human geneticist to the householder.
"Om'Obani" is not an easy piece, each choir voice has a different text and also in a barely known foreign language: Zulu, a language spoken by eleven million people in South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique and in some areas of Swaziland.
Help for self-help
According to an estimate by UNAIDS, the United Nations AIDS Programme, there are approximately 34 million people infected with the HIV virus worldwide.
23.5 million of them live in southern Africa.
There are 245,000 AIDS orphans in Swaziland.
More than 40 per cent of the population is already HIV-positive.
The Voices for Africa association has found in Germany sponsors for the 180 AIDS orphans of the people of Esitjeni.
Seventy of them attend high school.
For 15 or 20 euros a month you can sponsor a child.
This contribution will cover the school's tuition, uniform and guarantee you a hot meal a day at the Gogo Center.
Imbongi means in Zulu "narrator of stories" or "panegirist".
In this room no one knows how to speak fluently this Bantu language, but they do know how to sing.
For ten years this choir has been playing songs in this soft foreign language that sometimes manages to transport them to their place of origin: southern Africa.
At 8,733 kilometers in a straight line from Heidelberg, in the northeast of the Kingdom of Swaziland, there is a village called Esitjeni that depends on the voices of this German choir.
Forty percent are infected.
Approximately 2,000 people live there, some still in simple mud huts and straw, a large part of them are children.
More than 300 no longer have parents because they have succumbed to AIDS.
Esitjeni is a small example of what affects Swaziland: the highest rate of AIDS infection and the lowest life expectancy in the world, according to Unicef.
The population does not welcome circumcision, a practice that has been shown to reduce the risk of contagion by half.
More than 40 per cent of the population of Swaziland are carriers of the immunodeficiency virus, and dying with just over thirty years has become commonplace.
During a joint trip to Africa in the spring of 2005 the choir discovered this remote population, but what they saw mostly were many children in the streets who lacked not only the protection of their parents, but the main thing: food, clothing and training.
Without a school degree, possibilities in a poor country are more than limited.
At first it was only the particular commitment of a few that made it possible for a child to go to school and enjoy a hot meal a day. All this for a few euros.
A year later, however, the choir founded the association "Voices for Africa" which has since taken professional care of AIDS orphans in Esitjeni.
Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Among the STDs of bacterial origin are syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
The most common viral STDs are AIDS, the human papillomavirus, genital herpes, or hepatitis.
Scabies and scabies are among parasites-borne STDs.
What are the main groups affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur more often in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of five cases of syphilis registered in Germany originate from sexual contact between men.
In the case of heterosexual adults, the most common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydia, trichomonas, human papillomavirus, candidiasis (fungal) and gonorrhea.
HIV transmission among heterosexual adults in the country is relatively low; however, approximately 20 per cent of new HIV infections are recorded in this group.
Among young people, chlamydia infections are much more common than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In our country, the human papillomavirus is also added to the most common diseases among young people.
How has the number of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to mandatory declaration.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been declining since 2007.
Approximately 2,700 cases were recorded in 2011.
This is one tenth less than in the previous year.
What symptoms indicate that this is a venereal disease?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort when urinating, flow, abdominal pain, as well as blisters or warts.
They often do not cause pain or other symptoms and are therefore not detected.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not offer 100 percent protection.
Some sexually transmitted disease pathogens can also be transmitted through dirt infections and physical contact.
For this reason, experts recommend regular medical examinations, especially if you often change sexual partners.
If diagnosed early, most STDs can be cured and any late consequences can be avoided.
