The mountain tour of Talysh could be described as wild and romantic.
The minibus advances with great strep through the winding road that passes next to forested hills, rivers of great flow and the simple houses of local farmers.
It's all green and juicy, one might even think it's in the Black Forest.
However, we are in the southernmost part of Azerbaijan; from here the border with Iran is just a few kilometres away.
Here live the talyshi, a village of which not much is known, apart from that they perfectly dominate the Persian and Azeri and that are very long-lived.
Our final destination is Lerik.
This small town boasts perhaps too solid architecture designed in the Soviet era and which does not seem to fit fully into such a picturesque mountain landscape.
European tourists barely reach this place, as the road from Azerbaijan's capital, Baku, is too heavy.
To travel the 323 kilometers that separate both urban centers, it takes eight hours because the road is one-way.
The amazing wealth enjoyed by the country thanks to the oil from the Caspian Sea has not yet reached this remote region.
However, Pilata Fatulayeva (48) is convinced that Lerik has what it takes to become a tourist attraction.
"Baku became famous in May on the occasion of the Eurovision Festival and next year we will celebrate the Festival of the oldest people in the world," says Fatulayeva.
This is the director of the Longevity Museum, perhaps the only one in the world.
Here is documented the lives of eight dozen talyshis of the place who have exceeded 100 years of age. Fatulayeva points out a black and white image.
This is my grandfather, who lived 120 years.
His son died at the age of 136
However, the undisputed star of the museum is the sheep herder Şirali Müslümov, who appears to have lived 168 years.
However, there is no birth certificate certifying it.
And if we take into account that the documented older man lived 122 years, it seems that Müslümov's age is quite suspicious.
"He was born in the region in 1805 and died in 1973," Fatulayeva explains.
The man was married three times and had 23 children. Apparently he still had time to conceive one more daughter at the age of 136.
Has Şirali Müslümov been wrong in his age in a couple of decades?
However, Rembrandt Scholz, a gerontologist at the Max Planck Institute in Rostock, has also heard of the advanced age of this Central Asian inhabitant.
