In fact, the 234 articles, whose approval has been forced by a constituent assembly composed of 100 predominantly Islamist members at a 15-hour evening meeting, are truly worrying.
As in previous constitutions, the draft also states that jurisprudence is based on the “principles of Islamic law”.
However, what does that mean by "principles"?
This was and remains open to interpretation and it seems that Islamists will take advantage of this vague formulation, as well as the legal room for manoeuvre that it entails, to impose a stricter interpretation of sharia law.
This is at least what an added new article suggests: in all matters concerning sharia it is mandatory to consult Al-Ashar University, the most important Islamic institution in the country with great power throughout Sunni Islamism.
It does not have to be so, but this may mean that the clergy would control the legislation, which - in fact - would result in the incapacitation of the judiciary.
Much of the draft constitution is open to interpretation
What is also problematic is that it intends to maintain military jurisdiction.
During Mubarak's dictatorship these courts served to exert harsh repression on the opposition.
Following the fall of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were detained in military prisons.
As the draft states, the State must protect "the true essence of the Egyptian family" and "promote its morale and values".
It is a formulation so vague in legal terms that with the help of this article state institutions could even control the contents of cinematography and literature.
Clearly speaking, this is nothing but censorship.
Indeed, no article explicitly establishes equality between men and women.
Instead another forbids offending or slandering Prophet Mohammed and his legacies.
However, it is not clear what an offence is and how it is to be punished.
Just as doubtful is the formulation that prohibits “offensive to people”
Is a cartoon of the president enough or a joke about a lawyer?
Question of interpretation, like many other things in the draft which has been presented to Mursi for signature and which, according to his words, "very soon" will be presented to the Egyptians for referendum.
"The Revolution Is Back"
The opposition has been closing ranks against the superiority of Islamists for weeks.
Ten thousand people gathered in unusual harmony on Friday afternoon at Tahrir Square in the Cario and vowed to make the Act fail before it can come into effect.
