And several judges announced that they did not want to oversee the referendum, so it would not be considered valid.
"The Qur'an is our constitution"
For its part, the well-organized Muslim community called for a counter-demonstration; in case not in Tahrir Square, but after a prayer across the Nile, before Cairo University.
Many women covered with a veil and supporters of the Salafists took part in it to the cry of "the people demand the application of the divine law".
They demanded that Mursi "clean up the country," while proclaiming: "The Koran is our constitution."
A struggle for the sovereignty of the symbolic Tahrir Square, where everything began, would have provoked a situation similar to that of a civil war.
It is clear that Mursi's supporters did not want to risk something like this happening.
The Muslim brothers claimed that both those who oppose the draft constitution and its supporters would have expressed their views loud and clear.
Now the time would have come to let the people decide at the polls what direction the country should follow.
In this sense, it seems that the draft of the Islamists is guaranteed the majority.
"The expression 'Human Rights' doesn't even appear"
Hafez Abu Saeda is furious with this forced constitutional process that should have actually lasted until February and included all social forces.
This 48-year-old lawyer specializing in human rights and president of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EOHR) defended the Muslim brothers when they were held in prison or had to face a trial during Mubarak's dictatorship.
Not because he shared his ideology, but because for him human rights are indivisible.
For this reason he was beaten, convicted and imprisoned.
"And now the expression `Human Rights' does not even appear in the new constitution," laments in a conversation with the newspaper "Welt am Sonntag".
The extension of Mursi's powers to the three branches of government led to his resignation.
The measures taken are flagrant violations of the rules of the democratic game and will lead Egypt to a new dictatorship.
"Instead of strengthening civil society, what the president has done is abolish it," Saeda laments.
However, democracy cannot function without civil society organizations.
Saeda feels abandoned, also by the international community, which observes the ideological struggle that is taking place on the banks of the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
This could turn against you.
A protester in Tahrir Square warns: "You are conceiving a monster that you will not be able to control."
Norwegian rakfisk: the world's most smelly fish?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the country's success has any bearing on its greed for a highly smelly fish?
Take a number of excessively cured cheeses.
Put them in the middle of a mountain of dirty, wet football clothes.
Leave it there for a week.
Then you can smell the paralyzing aroma of rakfisk, one of Norway's delicacies.
I'm in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
The landscape is spectacular and that smell, always present, floats in the air.
The rakfisk is salted trout that is fermented in water during, depending on how smelly you prefer, up to a year.
As it gets darker and colder, Norwegians flock to a festival held here in Fagernes, dedicated to this most captivating delicacy, so to speak, captivating.
"You eat raw and then drink a glass of aquavit from a drink," says Havard Halvarsen, a city firefighter who is also known as the "General of the Rakfisk", who organizes the festival.
Everywhere we see people eating this fish that is kept in small buckets and drinking important amounts of the drink from a drink.
"Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk," Havard says.
Drink can kill the smell.
I try some pieces.
If you can avoid passing it near your nose, it's not bad; it's not very different from a portion of sushi that has traveled a few kilometers by bus.
The rakfisk is a product that comes from a very different time, when poverty hit Norway and where, before cooling, fish was kept during the autumn submerged in water and salt in airtight barrels.
Later, in the middle of winter, when it is already fermented, it is taken out and, evidently with inactive senses due to alcohol, it is eaten.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, and emigrated mainly to the United States.
Today, the population is growing rapidly; more than 13 per cent are immigrants, attracted by the abundance of jobs, high wages and a comprehensive system of social services.
A stream of inhabitants of Sweden, the old rival and until not too much richer than Norway, arrives in this country to work.
The rakfisk is considered to be an important, albeit rather smelly, part of Norway's past.
It is among the most expensive dishes you can buy.
But, in fact, everything is expensive. A beer cane or a sandwich cost you the coldness of 10€ ($14) each.
Norway does not usually appear on the international news agenda and most Norwegians like it to be so.
Here people are still unwilling to pronounce the name Anders Breivik, the far-right racist who shot and killed 77 people, including men, women and children.
Instead, they refer to the shooting as "the event of July 22".
Norwegians find it very difficult to believe that in their peaceful country one of their own was capable of committing such cruelty and murder.
After much of Norway's present wealth lies the growth, since the early 1970s, of one of the world's largest oil and gas industries.
"But oil is not the only reason we're doing so well," says Anna, our waitress, as she passes rakfisk trays and, with her long blonde hair and her amazing blue eyes, represents the image of Norwegian well-being.
"We are, as you say, prudent people."
His English, like that of most people in this country, is impeccable.
"We don't like to brag, we don't like flaunting."
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution; everything except a small percentage of the money coming from this industry is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone was wasting money that they did not have during the years leading up to the financial crisis around the world, Norway kept the wallet tightly closed.
"As long as we can ski in winter and hike in summer, we're happy," says Anna.
"And eat rakfisk," he adds with an unwrapped laugh.
I'm in the snow lining up to eat something; I've had enough rakfisk.
Now a moose burger is certainly something different and quite succulent to taste.
But at night, that smelly fish comes back.
The hotel where I stay is one of the many places where a rakfisk dinner is held where diners vote the best fish, or perhaps the one that tests the nostrils the most.
A television has connected live with a presenter wearing bow tie and surrounded by rakfisk dishes.
Looks like the Eurovision contest.
"What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
"Here's our score, Havard."
There's laughter and applause.
A man falls off the chair, perhaps beaten by the aquavit.
Or maybe it's the fumes of all that fish.
Mexico: Enrique Peña Nieto Faces Hard Start · Global Voices
As Mexico's incoming President Enrique Peña Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant analyzes the challenges the new president will face and the different expectations of his population.
Traffic in Mexico City is especially bad today.
In a city that, under the best circumstances, is already congested, a steel fence has been installed since Monday that cuts several of the main roads leading to the city and is causing enormous chaos on the roads.
The aim, however, was not to prevent workers from reaching their workplace, but to prevent protesters from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto, will receive the presidential band and assume the nation's management.
He faces a complicated task.
Mexico has been getting good economic results during the outgoing government of Felipe Calderón, but the country is immersed in a war against narcotraffic that has already claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
"My government has the great commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence," Peña Nieto explained earlier this week to the President of the United States, Barack Obama, at the Oval Office.
"I'm going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve that goal."
Before rubbing shoulders with the president of the United States, Mr. Peña's previous political experience was as governor of his native state, that of Mexico.
A very populated and rapidly growing state, surrounding the capital; Opinions about the new leader are divided into this territory in which he used to move.
A sincere man.
In the bucolic city of Valle del Bravo, for example, he is fondly remembered.
Its residents attribute to it the merit of the growth of on-site tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To get to the city you can drive on one of Mr. Peña Nieto's new roads, which is a huge improvement compared to the cracked and bumpy roads that were rehabilitated.
You can also see plaques with their name at the entrance of a modern sports centre and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We trust that he will make a real and lasting change," says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernández, deputy of the party of Mr. Peña Nieto, the PRI.
"In particular, in terms of security and economics, we look forward to the interesting and real change that our country needs so much."
After an uninterrupted period of 81 years in power, the PRI was unbanked by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that, after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, there are many expectations within the party regarding Enrique Peña Nieto.
It also rejects the qualification that the opposition lacks the essence of the new president.
"He is a very sincere man, very committed and with an excellent vision of the country.
He is a fantastic man of state and, above all, he is a person who knows how to listen."
However, on the other side of the state that's not the impression many people have about their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Neza City, the contrast with the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
Hidden under elevated highway sections is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems of the municipality are also hard and urban.
Earlier this year, military intervention was called for to assist in the fight against drug gangs operating in neighbourhoods, and violence against women is particularly serious.
In a desert plot, next to a garbage dump, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been abandoned in just the last two years.
More than 1,000 women were killed in the state of Mexico while Mr. Peña Nieto was the governor, a much higher rate than that of Ciudad Juárez, unfortunately famous for its violence and a place that is synonymous with the murder of innocent women.
Critics of Mr. Peña Nieto say, at best, that he did not know how to address the problem of femicide while in office.
The most critical accuse his administration of turning a blind eye.
In a concrete house, typical of the damaged neighborhood, Irinea Buendía has to make efforts to contain the tears while showing me photographs of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the facts, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that her partner murdered her.
"When I got home, it seemed as if his body had been cleaned," recalls Mrs.Buendía.
"There were signs that she had been beaten and rigor mortis had already appeared."
While her mother tells the story, a photograph of Mariana watches from the walls, next to a cross in which one word is read: Justice.
However, that is exactly what the family says it has been denied.
"The state authorities have treated me like I'm an old gossiper, a troublemaker, a whiner.
What they want is for you to simply accept what they say and shut up."
"But that can't be the case when there have been so many irregularities and so much negligence," he says.
The presidential band that President Peña Nieto will receive on Saturday will be accompanied by a huge responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by violent crimes in Mexico for the past six years and the new president has promised to give them priority during their term.
"I hope he's the same kind of president he was when he was governor," says PRI deputy Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
However, that is precisely what the families of the victims of Neza City fear the most.
Bradley Manning did not report ill-treatment, prosecutors claim
Prosecutors try to address Bradley Manning's allegations of abuse while in prison
The trial focuses on Manning's period at Quantico Military Prison in Virginia
The defense wants the case dismissed on the grounds that Manning's imprisonment was severe.
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of confidential information in United States history, missed multiple opportunities to report the ill-treatment he now claims to have suffered while in military detention.
During the prosecution's interrogation of Manning at a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, prosecutor Commander Ashden Fein stated that the records of weekly visits by unit officers Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, do not show any complaints about the treatment he received.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing following the defence ' s request to dismiss the case since his imprisonment had been harsh and had already resulted in sufficient punishment, came one day after Manning had testified that he had thought of committing suicide while in detention.
The army's intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
Later, WikiLeaks published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of information.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that officers filled out after visits to Manning during his arrest at Quantico military prison, where he was imprisoned in maximum detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers would have asked Manning questions and written down his answers.
When asked about the forms on Friday Fein, Manning acknowledged that he had qualified the treatment given to him by the warders as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facilities in general as "very professional".
The forms do not show any allegations of ill-treatment, despite the fact that the officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he received, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the visiting officers had spoken about those problems and had indicated that they would be dealt with, but that they did not record those issues in the register.
"They wrote 'no incidents' (after having talked about the problems) but this does not necessarily mean that I had not mentioned any problems," Manning said.
The judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why she had not denounced the treatment she received during the meeting that took place in January 2011 with a council to examine the suicide intentions she had expressed on a form months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during that meeting was to obtain a reduction in the "injury prevention" regime under which he was under.
The military said that they had placed him under this restrictive regime, which is below the level of surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know that I was fine and (I wanted) to stop being under injury prevention... so I could enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for almost two months before being transferred to the military prison located at the Marine base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered committing suicide in Kuwait and once lost consciousness because of the heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced only to Camp Arafjon, to that cage," Manning explained on Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning claimed that, once transferred to Quantico, he spent most of the days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he was trying to move all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed he always had a light coming from outside pointing to his eyes while he slept.
He said that if the wardens could not see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn again.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint in January 2011 regarding Manning's treatment.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth military prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday the judge asked Manning about an allegation he had made in Thursday's statement that, after being forced one night to sleep naked in his Quantico cell, he was forced during a morning count to stand naked in front of the guards and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said he deduced from the order given to him by the warden that he should drop the blanket he could have covered himself with, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he posed no danger to himself.
Manning claimed that he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic on his underwear or his flip flops to self-harm but that he had not.
Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell that night.
His lawyers hoped that the judge would at least take into account the experiences he had spent while in prison and drastically reduce his sentence in case he was convicted at the court martial, which was scheduled to begin early next year.
The defense stated that it plans to have Manning plead guilty to misdemeanor crimes and defend other charges considered too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has maintained that Manning was held under the rules of application to every detainee in full custody in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, illegally provoking the posting of information on the Internet, leaking information from the national defense, and theft of property or public records.
If he's found guilty on all counts, he could face life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis
He claims that many were forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to criticize those who left; they say they remember Mexicans from those difficult times
Navarrette comments that Mexican-Americans are trapped between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, he had barely come down the esplanade and reached the immigration processing area and was already completely confused.
Some signs pointed the way to two queues: one for "Mexicans" and one for "Foreigners".
I stayed there for a few seconds without being sure where I should go.
Growing up in Central California, I've been called "Mexican" all my life.
This is ethnic shorthand, just as my friends in Boston refer to themselves as "Irish" or my friends in New York call themselves "Italians."
Later I decided to "Mexican-American."
But this was Mexico.
And, in my grandfather's homeland, shorthand or scripts were not necessary.
He was simply an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to handle myself during an interview in this language.
But I don't have the vocabulary level of a native and I can't get rid of my American accent.
So I took my American passport and put myself in the queue of foreigners.
I thought about that moment this week when Mexico's elected president, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
The agenda of the day, as always when the leaders of these two countries meet, included: immigration, drugs and trade.
Peña Nieto was also looking forward to talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, one of the reasons why at the moment it is as likely that a Mexican will stay in Mexico as he will venture to go to the United States.
He wants to partner with the United States and Canada and create a European Union-style trade bloc in North America.
In addition, Peña Nieto promised to continue fighting drug cartels in Mexico, although he did not give details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never remember that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to cede half of its territory at gunpoint.
But for Mexicans, who think in centuries, not minutes, the elements that remind them are everywhere.
So, the moment a U.S. official says anything that brings the slightest criticism to Mexico, you start hearing complaints, both in the press and among the Mexican elite, about how Americans are usurping the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the sons of Moctezuma stand up for war.
And yet, for Mexico, the relationship that really poses a challenge is that with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
Are we talking about grudges?
There's a lot.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people for whom the country provides opportunities and others for whom it does not.
The only reason there are so many people of Mexican descent living in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that, somewhere in our family tree, there was one person, maybe the father or mother or one of the grandparents, who was closed the door of opportunity in Mexico and had to march north.
And most of the time that person fit into a certain profile: dark skin, a low level of education, coming from a poor village, etc.
We are their descendents and we are loyal to them.
Not Mexico.
And, even though we may now be living the American dream, having gone to good schools and had good jobs, we can never lose sight of the fact that what we are living is that, the American dream, and not the Mexican dream.
Sometimes our identity may not be clear, but our loyalty is.
It's for the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many of the Mexicans belonging to the elite of the ruling class do not like us.
The feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look at us over the shoulder as if we were of a lower category that is not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough and our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
In his view, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And now we wouldn't find ourselves trapped behind this silk curtain, living well in the United States but still as lonely souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally came to the United States when she was a child, reminds me that there is this friction between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because the former know more solidly who they are and the latter this bothers them.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she is considered to be part of the two countries.
Meanwhile, many Mexican-Americans I know feel that they are not part of either.
We love listening to the Mexican group Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You have the best of every country, but you're not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico they see us as Americans.
And in the United States we are considered Mexican.
Now, to further complicate things, from what I have learned during my trip, some Mexican leaders and some intellectuals want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as impromptu "ambassadors" of Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We would tell our fellow Americans how fantastic it is to visit that country and pressure political leaders to strengthen their ties with Mexico.
Yeah, sure...
That's not gonna happen.
There's too much grudge.
And, with wage inequality, galloping corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure it's a fantastic country.
I'm afraid you're going to be left alone with this idea, folks.
Fair enough.
If some Mexicans are not yet prepared to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, then they have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still resentful of how their relatives were treated much less.
Hmm.
Maybe we're more Mexican than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas may well be an unlikely basis for peace
Can there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed that seems to indicate that any hope is in vain.
In the midst of useless and usual discussions about who started first, piles of buildings have been reduced to rubble; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed and, for the first time, missiles from Gaza have fallen near Tel Aviv, the metropolis of Israel, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But, despite the fact that Israelis and Palestinians seem to be anchored in their former conflict, everything around them in the Middle East is changing.
The Arab spring has left everything torn apart whether you like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have been caught up in the regional commotion.
Perhaps this will make your struggle even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to believe that their lethal impasse could de-escalate.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism now seems very difficult to justify.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on 21 November is maintained, this week's clashes have reinforced the hawks on both sides.
Hamas leaders, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced Israelis to withdraw, even though Gaza has been badly beaten.
And despite having killed some of its leaders and put the 1.7 million inhabitants of Gaza under pressure in one of the most miserable and populated corners of the world, Israel has not been able to end Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently ruled by its unrelenting rivals of Fatah, the most moderate Palestinian faction.
In addition, Hamas leaders could conclude that time is on their side.
As Islamists have gained influence throughout the Arab world, Hamas has made rich and powerful friendships.
Turkey, a reborn regional power that had previously been the closest Muslim ally to Israel, has embraced the cause of Hamas, as has Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic states in the Gulf.
Exultant Hamas members say that the Islamist crescent is encircling Israel, from Lebanon to the north, where Hizbulah militant party dominates, passing through Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist tendency could overthrow Bashar Assad, until they reach Jordan, where Hamas allies are threatening the king.
Especially on the southern flank of Israel, the growth of Muslim Brothers led by President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and fundamental in Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until its fall in 2011, did not have much time for Hamas.
Instead, the Muslim Brotherhood are brotherly cousins of Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular opinion.
In future diplomatic actions, Hamas may emerge as a protagonist that cannot be excluded, not even Israel and the United States.
Meanwhile, Israel's hard wing will draw the contrary conclusion.
As far as the military issue is concerned, Hamas has been put on its site.
Israel's Iron Dome anti-missile system has proved its effectiveness and many of Hamas' missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will sleep quieter... for some time.
With regard to diplomacy, the United States was firmer than ever; many European countries also blamed Hamas for having started the latest wave of violence.
Above all, Israel has prospered. Especially under the rule of Benjamin Netanyahu, a prime minister who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets fired from Gaza have killed some 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has not had too many suicide bombers, partly because of the barrier that corrodes the West Bank, the main piece of territory aspiring to become a state of Palestine, and protects Jewish settlements that continue to increase despite the fact that, under international law, they are illegal.
Mr Netanyahu, whose Likud party has joined an even harder line group led by Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the elections on 22 January, is in a good position.
Why spoil those twisted Palestinians by giving them a state of their own?
If they really ruled the West Bank, wouldn't they fire rockets just like their compatriots have done in Gaza?
It's better to have them behind that wall and give them a good blow if they raise their heads.
The hard wing may be imposed, although the Arab spring might alter its calculations.
Although Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere do not have too much appreciation for Israel, their priority will be to address internal difficulties.
Israel's defence budget is greater than that of its four Arab neighbours together.
Starting a war with the area's superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to improve their economies.
That pragmatic Mr. Morsi has worked with Barack Obama to achieve the ceasefire is a good omen and could mark the beginning of something.
Israelis should also think long-term.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination means creating a powder keg that will one day explode in the territories occupied by Israel, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state and demography worsens the situation as the Arab population increases.
The bloody missions to Gaza every two or three years to reject Hamas will pay an ever-increasing diplomatic toll.
Both sides need a push from people outside the conflict.
The solution remains that of sensible people on both sides, most of the outside world and this newspaper: two states and Israel's transfer of territory for security reasons.
The hope, small in the short term, is that the ceasefire will give a little more impetus to others who are fighting for this cause.
Egypt, which must begin to curb the entry of arms into Gaza, along with Turkey and Qatar, is in an unprecedented situation to convince Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, with land exchanges and a shared Jerusalem.
Arabs outside the issue should also pressure Hamas and Fatah to join.
That would contribute more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the imminent attempt to obtain a virtual state category at the UN.
Mr. Obama also has an important role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term he omitted to present his own peace plan.
Again in the White House, he seems just as reluctant to devote his attention to him.
This attitude is a deplorable vision for the future.
A stable Middle East is of vital interest to the United States.
This implies a peace agreement between Israel and Palestine.
Generic Tobacco Packaging Act enters into force in Australia
Warnings about the risks of smoking and parts of the body with diseases are displayed on cartons of a green off color, which are the same for all brands of tobacco
Australian law on tobacco and generic packaging, pioneer in the world, comes into effect and replaces the logos and colors of the brands with a wrapper of an olive green shutdown, frightening images of body parts with diseases and depictions of sick children and babies as children of smokers.
With the exception of the different images and sanitary warnings, the only difference between the packs, mandatory since Saturday, are the names of the marks, all printed on a small type of source.
This is the strictest regime in the world applied to tobacco packaging.
The federal government of Australia states that the goal is to deter young people from smoking by removing the features that make this habit glamour.
He relies on studies that show that if a person has not started smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that he will never do so.
"It can be seen that children, even from a very early age, understand the message that the tobacco company is trying to sell through its brand," said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that showed, for example, how girls related the logo of a crown to the idea of being a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and these changes will not affect the profits of multinationals too much, other countries are considering similar measures.
The tobacco industry has exerted enormous pressure against the law.
Tobacco companies claimed that the law would promote the black tobacco market, where cigarettes would be cheaper and more accessible.
"The legislation will have serious unintended consequences," said Scott McIntyre of the British American Tobacco in Australia.
It will increase the amount of tobacco that counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will bring to sell on the streets of Australia.
Other people say their business has benefited after the passage of the law.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, claimed that the demand for cigarette cases and silicone covers to cover up the nasty pictures of the packs had skyrocketed almost from scratch two months ago, when the British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost a challenge to the law in the Supreme Court of Australia.
Ms. Ha stated that Zico had sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale establishments and that she was waiting for more stocks.
"To us it's a good deal."
According to experts, the possible obstacle is the popularity of social networks among the demographic sector targeted by the plan.
Following a series of Australian laws prohibiting television advertising and sports sponsorship and forcing most vendors not to put cigarettes in sight, tobacco marketing has now moved on to online marketing.
Australia has banned Internet advertising to local companies and websites, but cannot restrict it on foreign pages.
"If you market tobacco and you only have this little window left to promote your products, online space is the most compelling place to be," said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman observed an increase in brand reviews from "foot citizens" posted on social media websites such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
One wonders if this is just a private citizen who really loves Marlboro cigars and has taken the trouble of making a video or if any marketing company is behind it all.
The British American Tobacco of Australia indicated that the industry focuses more on what new regulation implies than on marketing.
Industry has even paid for Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules; these countries are asserting to the World Trade Organization that trade is being unjustly restricted, despite the fact that none of these countries have significant trade volumes with Australia.
The WTO is likely to issue a resolution in mid-2013.
Plibersek claimed that the government had held discussions with other countries that are considering implementing similar tobacco packaging laws.
In 2001 Canada became the first country to introduce the mandatory inclusion of images in packets.
They are currently mandatory in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
In Britain, New Zealand, South Africa and India, tougher laws are being considered.
In Australia many smokers are defiant.
"Photographs don't affect me.
I just don't listen to them."
"You take the cigar and keep the package," says Victor El Hage as he buys a package with the image of a tumor in his mouth.
"Sincerely, there's only one reason I'd quit smoking: for my daughter."
James Yu, manager of the King of the Pack pond in central Sydney, indicates that uniform packs make it more difficult for him to place them on shelves.
"It usually took an hour to unwrap a delivery; now it takes me four," Yu says.
"The government should have totally banned tobacco and then, that's it, okay, it's over and we shut down the store," he says as he raises his hands up.
In a constantly connected world, it's not so bad to get a little bored.
During the Thanksgiving holidays this year, unexpectedly I had to spend five hours at an airport because the plane we were flying in suffered a mechanical problem and we had to wait for another plane to arrive.
So I had a lot of time to think about boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Spending half a day at an airport waiting for a flight is rather boring, even if you have the means to be entertained, such as books, magazines or iPhones, without forgetting about duty-free stores.
But more and more scholars and experts in child development praise the benefits of boredom.
According to them, it is well that, both we and our children, we get bored from time to time.
Boring forces the brain to look for interesting options and may encourage creativity.
Since, at present, most of us are connected to this or that screen, we do not experience the benefits of boredom.
So should we accept boredom in good spirits?
Yeah.
And no.
But we'll talk about it later.
First, like many people, I assumed that, now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of the book "Boredom: A Lively History" ("Boredom, An Animated History") published in 2011 by Yale University Press, does not.
"In fact, the history of boredom is very extensive," he says.
On the walls of Pompeii there are graffiti in Latin about boredom dating from the 1st century AD.
We must also consider how we define boredom.
"The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in a variety of ways," says John D. Eastwood, professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada.
After examining published research and putting the idea before a 100-person discussion group, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "wanting, but not being able, to participate in an activity that fills you."
He claims that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person does not do something but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do anything.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is "the alteration of the attention process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly."
Boring can sound terribly like depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that, although they may be related, people who are bored tend to see the problem as a question of the environment or the world, while people who are depressed consider the problem to be theirs.
Sometimes we think we're bored, when what's really happening to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In his study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in the September edition of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups heard in the adjoining room a full-volume television show that was unrelated, others listened to it with low volume, so it was barely noticeable, while the third group did not listen to the audio at any time.
The group that listened to the program with the low volume showed more boredom than the other two groups; they found it difficult to concentrate, but they were not sure why and attributed it to boredom.
"When you try to focus on a difficult or interesting task, attention disruption can lead to boredom," said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at Guelph University in Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
"On the other hand, when you're doing something boring, like detecting faulty pieces in a manufacturing line, distracting music can help you not to get bored."
"In fact, we currently know that moving or scribbles, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help combat it, as they make that person more physically alert."
"Research shows that those children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to stand still," says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it's like to get bored at some point: the delay of an airplane, a monotonous speaker, a particularly boring movie.
But some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To help measure it, some researchers developed a "trend to boredom scale" in the 1980s.
The scale includes issues such as "many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous" and "there are so many things that interest me that I don't have time to do everything."
Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, states that using these scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored than girls, and specifically need more external and more varied stimulation.
But, in general, teenagers are a type of group that gets bored quite easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day through a pager.
He discovered that 32 percent of teenagers said they were bored while in school or doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when they were not in school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether current boredom rates, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he said what he did know was that "adolescence is a period in which boredom reaches its highest heights," largely because both children and adolescents are not given much control over what they want to do.
So, back to my question at the beginning: Is it good to get bored?
Sometimes it is not, because, taken to the extreme, it can cause us to expose ourselves to absurd physical risks, such as betting or falling into the use of substances as a method of combating it, as research shows.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers talk about the connection between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this issue for more than two decades.
"Boredom is the brain's way of telling you that you should be doing something else," says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn't always know what's most appropriate.
If you're bored and use that energy to play guitar or cook, that will satisfy you.
But if you watch TV, it may satisfy you in the short term, but not in the long run.
"So, if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he may not be bored anymore, but he won't have learned to entertain himself or dose himself," Professor Fenske says.
And "that ability to dose applies to other situations," he says.
Not only does your child learn to entertain himself, but he learns to better control himself in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
But we shouldn't be too critical of him either.
Our goal should be, rather, to be comfortable away from the constant rumor of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"In our view, we need to be more bored, but boredom is too distressing and disturbing a desire to relate it to something worthwhile," he says.
He points out that what people are really looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy a dead time.
"In an environment in which we are constantly overstimulated," he says, "it's hard to find ways to focus our attention when noise stops."
