Petronella Wyatt: "I was harassed until I got kicked out of Oxford for being a Tory"
College students are not attacked for their views only now
I don't remember any time in my life that I haven't been dreaming about getting a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had been in which I supposed was the best place in the world to learn, a Greek symposium of the contemporary era that fostered the two pillars of civilization: free thought and tolerance.
However, within two weeks of taking up my position at Worcester College in the late 1980s to pursue the history career, I had already packed my bags, which triggered the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and wept.
My friends were baffled.
The Evening Standard newspaper claimed that I had abandoned because I did not tolerate some college classmates having sex in the next room.
Writer A. N. Wilson announced jokingly that I had left because I was forced to drink in discounted cups.
The truth was less fun.
I ran away from there.
Yes, I fled, because I had been subjected to systematic harassment and intimidation.
Not because of my extravagant name, or the fact that I came from a private school.
I was harassed for a single reason, which in the cradle of the alleged illustration was somewhat intolerant and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a prominent advisor to Margaret Thatcher and I supported the conservative party.
You might wonder what that's about now.
Well, several reports indicate that a new generation of center-right students are suffering similar persecution.
The institutionalized and growing hatred towards students of the conservative party is such in Oxford that, last week, a group of them claimed the same level of equal rights as homosexuals, the disabled and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the JCR (grouping of undergraduate students) of Corpus Christi College claim that they are "often seriously sidelined, personally attacked, and treated as unwelcome people" for their political ideas.
They want to create a position on their college's equal opportunities committee to make sure they can express their views freely.
Their situation was not favoured by a recent BBC2 documentary called "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right" about student politics and presenting the Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazi.
He showed graduate student Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Party Association (OUCA), in a Rolls-Royce, wearing a silver suit and a cane with the silver hilt.
At other universities, conservative students say they are treated as "Turkish heads" for the introduction of higher tuition fees.
Luke Black, 20, vice president of the Conservative Party Association at Nottingham University, stated in a Sunday paper that "there is a growing left-wing trend in universities.
People assume we're like the Bullingdon Club without even knowing each other."
Samuel Roberts, 21-year-old history student at Corpus Christi who filed the motion for greater protection, claims that this environment is "uncomfortable," while 19-year-old OUCA president-elect Stephanie Cherill claims that the attitude of JCR members towards people who are center right has worsened.
"This poses a threat to the environment of intellectual debate, as well as to the well-being of members," he says.
During my first weeks at Oxford I was more lonely than 1:00.
I entered college in September 1986, I was a terribly shy 18-year-old girl.
Hatred of the Conservative Party was at its highest point.
The previous year, the university had voted to deny Margaret Thatcher, a former student, a title "honoris causa" following cuts in funding for Higher Education.
The atmosphere would have shocked any Stalinist.
Already during the first days of the week of welcome to the new university students, when the new students meet and meet the professors, I received a sample of the bitterness that awaited me.
I discovered that the professors not only turned a blind eye to the mockery of conservative college students, but willingly participated in it.
The policy of miners' strike, privatization and government opposition to apartheid sanctions in South Africa reached the seminar's wooden halls.
The first one I attended was to translate 18th century French texts into English and I was not prepared for what came next.
"Miss Wyatt," said Professor Harry Pitt (already deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I didn't say one.
Pitt, a short man with a face that looked like cake dough, knew well how to expel bad bile.
"Is it that the Thatcherists refuse to learn French or are they simply fools?" he asked.
The other college kids laughed.
My eyes were burning from the tears I was trying to contain.
"I suggest you go to French lessons in your spare time, as long as you're not too busy meeting people," Pitt grunted.
I returned to my room as a soul in sorrow.
That night I sat alone at dinner time in college; then I felt a slight pat on the back.
He was a sophomore English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the OUCA.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
"I'm afraid that's how it goes.
They mess with anyone who's suspected of being Tory.
It's very complicated for me, but they know your father's close to Margaret Thatcher, so it'll be even worse for you.
Many newly arrived Tories appear to be Labourers."
Later, in a local pub, I tried cowardly to hide.
I insisted that he disagreed with everything Mrs Thatcher said.
That trick proved useless.
A freshman in Philosophy, Politics and Economics who, paradoxically, had studied in Eton, said, "You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You're contaminated."
Other students adopted that little song.
I became the dirty pervert.
"How do Tories have sex?" one asked.
"They beat each other up, don't they?"
I felt the same way that homosexuals should have felt before the liberal law of the 1960s.
Could I ever lead a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to meet people who thought like me only after dusk?
Would I have to become a Labourer and repress my natural tendencies?
The three years that awaited me were presented as a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only professor openly Tory was Norman Stone, Professor of Contemporary History destined for my college.
He was hated for being not only of the Conservative party, but also thatcher's advisor in foreign policy and one of the people writing his speeches to him.
I was barely there.
He hated the place he considered provincial and insignificant and his adherence to the Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You're not going to be happy here," he told me.
I began to move daily from Oxford to my parents' home in London, finding refuge in my more open-minded metropolitan family and friends.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why.
He didn't believe me.
When he studied there in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said with sadness.
"They would never do that, not there among my dear dream needles.
Even my communist friends always had an impeccable attitude."
His sore eyes began to cloud.
"Give him another chance.
I'm sure they did it just to joke.
My heart would break if you left it."
Exhausted from so many trips to London, my emotional resistance was deteriorating.
A friend of mine, who also supported the Conservative Party, had succumbed to pressure and renounced his creed.
The following week, during a seminar in which another professor of history had hinted, speaking totally seriously, that I was an "enemy of the people", I decided to do the same.
Red with shame inside, I admitted that my parents had "washed my brain" and called them "stupid old men."
The truce lasted a short time.
It was my father who put the last nail in the coffin of my college career at Oxford.
At that time my father wrote two weekly columns in Murdoch's press.
My door was locked.
I was snuggled in fear and, after five minutes, my persecutors gave up.
When they left, I packed my bags and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
Maybe you call me weak crybaby.
But no 18-year-old should be subjected to such a level of intimidation and hostility in an educational institution.
What is even more tragic is that it was Oxford, which not only has formed 14 Prime Ministers of the Conservative Party but, to this day, hides behind an undeserved reputation of equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to notoriety"
On the occasion of the exhibition "Valentino: Maestro de la Costura", which opened this week in London, ABC talks with Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza and other famous clients of the Italian designer
Somerset House, former residence of Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition on Valentino Garavani.
The designer recognized him during the inauguration of "Valentino: Maestro de la Costura", a retrospective apotheosic that brings together more than 130 couture dresses created by his "maison" over the last 50 years.
"I love this palace," he says with his unmistakable Italian accent.
This exhibition is the culmination of a story whose only protagonist is "il signore" Garavani, but which could not have been written without its distinguished clients.
Valentino has always been fascinated by the rare and distant world of nobility.
