The hardest trade in the world: the human mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, Indonesian volcano porters play life and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone trails
There are people whose work is one hell and another who literally works in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living drawing sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to go down every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulphurous gas emanating from the bowels of the Earth solidifies when it comes into contact with the air.
After removing large sulfur rocks, which in total weigh about 70 kilos, he carries them in two baskets of bamboo that he loads on his shoulders through steep stone trails.
They are only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted porters take more than 40 minutes to climb at turtle's pace, keeping balance and groping their steps so as not to slip and fall down the cliff.
They know that any trip could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who took off years ago from the cliffs of the Kawah Ijen.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for each kilo of sulphur they extract
Once above, tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys open their way and, gruelingly carrying the heavy baskets, they walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little lower, at 1,850 meters high.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for every kilo of sulphur.
He then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to whiten sugar.
"As it is normal to carry 70 kilos, we take out about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," Anto explains, who usually carries three carriers a day.
It takes three hours each and ends up ground, but they allow him to gather 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems a misery for such an inhuman effort, it is three times what I would gain in the field.
"The miners' wages are very high here, where coffee collection is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly salary is 2 million rupees (167 euros) ", explains the porter, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, her salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the cut was not so hard, but Anto has returned with her family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a reason of weight that, in Indonesia, is as strong as sulfur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and is irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto has been playing his ass in the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to pay for it despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, he breathes with difficulty, he coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases that fire the volcano.
It's the price you have to pay to get your dream.
"I will work two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French," he promises in an English language that is more than acceptable.
Punished by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tourist guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, but instead he does the work of a mule.
Sharing an unclean wooden cabin with other porters, he gets up every day at 2 a.m. because sulfur does not stop working at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of darkness.
Challenging the shadows, Anto goes down to the crater lighting up with a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he himself has bought with his money.
About 400 porters load the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater
Despite its pungent profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur extraction to save costs or provide any equipment to the carriers, who work on their own and on their own weight.
In fact, they do not even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) of camera surcharge that, next to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This job is for the beasts and not for the people," says Madrusin, a 42-year-old strong porter who has been at the Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
Capable of lifting up to 110 kilos, he says he will endure working "as long as he can" because he needs the money to educate his three children, aged 18 to 10.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although sulfur burns the throat and stings the eyes when the wind changes suddenly and traps the miners in the thick columns that leave the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of serious illnesses ... beyond, of course, their usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, pains in the knees and sores on the shoulders, which have been malformed by the weight of the baskets.
Swinging the basket on his back, Unainik can only carry 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Every day, he and his companions start 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks move to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away by a goat road between the weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life," says Unainik, opening his mouth well, where he lacks several teeth.
Of his five children, the oldest, aged 30, also works carrying sulfur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest trades in the world: the one made by the human mules of the Kawah Ijen.
