Unasur Summit ends without making public the Lima Declaration
The Sixth Presidential Summit of the South American Union of Nations (Unasur) concluded today in Peru without the Lima Declaration, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven presidents present.
Efe tried repeatedly to access the document signed at the Sixth Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but sources of Foreign Ministry and Presidency indicated at the beginning that they would hand it over after the closure, but later stated that it would be published on the Peruvian Government's website at some point.
When consulted by the text, they pointed out that the content had been exposed by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during a few brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to Summit information was restricted at all times.
During the day, only the video without sound from the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room with the message "private session, restricted audio".
The little information that circulated among the reporters was handed over by the press spokespersons of some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, although not the Peruvian one.
The only document released during the day was the list of attending presidents, which caused the unrest of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more data.
Subsequently, the Peruvian Presidency sent an email to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but this is Humala's pronouncement, and not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South America-Arab Countries (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being insistently requested by the press, the so-called Lima Declaration that they had previously announced was also not disseminated.
On the official ASPA website it can be corroborated that the document was published last Tuesday.
In both international meetings, Peruvian authorities made efforts to ensure that transmission systems were secured for all journalists but limited information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a ruling of the Court of The Hague that would resolve a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and of Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (ICJ), which begins Monday in The Hague to hear the arguments of both parties, in the process that Lima presented against Santiago.
"We will address and execute the sentence that defines the differences that we are bringing to this international court today," said Humala, along with her Chilean pair.
"Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country respectful of international law, of the peaceful settlement of disputes, treaties and international tribunals," Piñera added, and greeted Humala with a handshake, along with the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they will submit to the ICJ occurred after Colombia denounced this week the Pact of Bogotá by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of that international tribunal, following a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered seriously wrong.
The summit was held with the absences of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was in charge of opening deliberations in the morning and closing the summit, shortly after noon in Lima.
The president read the final document in which he reported that 16 agreements were adopted and action lines were set for 31 projects among the South American countries for a total of $17 billion in investments.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries will give "significant steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship for which we are expanding the agreements on residence."
He reported that actions are being promoted to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, low-priced internet access in all corners of South America, and to deal jointly and efficiently with the risks of natural disasters."
With a Europe in crisis, "the economic consolidation (of Latin America) should not have a triumphalist matrix but should serve to expand our productive matrix and envision a better future for our peoples," Humala added.
"We have decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas...uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," said the Peruvian president in a read message.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located in the cross-cutting axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give more details.
The outcome document also mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve for its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region of prosperity and peace and good relations among neighbours was another issue highlighted by the summit.
In this regard, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before beginning his participation in the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his pair from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to treat the maritime dispute respectfully after a ruling of the ICJ, questioned by Bogotá.
"Tomorrow (Saturday) may have an encounter with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We are going to review all these paths, they are not exclusive, even the treaty with Nicaragua will require a conversation with Nicaragua," he stressed.
"With President Ortega I hope I can tell him to handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet on Saturday in Mexico where they plan to attend the inauguration of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Also, as part of the summit, the Defense Ministers of the bloc met in advance to adopt the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defense in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the last country is suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
